  "response": "The northern island of Hokkaido was the last major part of Japan to be extensively settled by ethnic Japanese. Prior to the Meiji period (starting in 1868), Hokkaido was primarily inhabited by the indigenous Ainu people. Systematic Japanese colonization and settlement of Hokkaido began in the late 19th century, with significant government-sponsored migration and development programs. The Tohoku region in northern Honshu was also one of the later areas to be fully integrated into Japanese society, with significant settlement and development occurring during the Edo and Meiji periods.",
